## Core Mitigation Strategies for PHP XSS


## 1. Context-Aware Output Encoding (Primary Defense)
Never trust user data printed to the screen. Convert dangerous characters into safe HTML entities before rendering them.

* For HTML Body: Use htmlspecialchars() with ENT_QUOTES and UTF-8 encoding.

echo htmlspecialchars($user_input, ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8');

* For JavaScript Context: If you must pass PHP variables into JavaScript blocks, use json_encode() instead of standard printing.

<script>
    let userName = <?php echo json_encode($user_input); ?>;
</script>


## 2. Implement Content Security Policy (CSP)
A CSP is an HTTP response header that restricts the resources (like JavaScript files) that the browser is allowed to load and execute. It acts as a safety net if your encoding fails.

* Add this header to your PHP code to block all inline scripts (like <script>alert(1)</script>):

header("Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self';");


## 3. Strict Input Validation (Allow-listing)
Filter data as soon as the PHP application receives it. Drop any unexpected characters before processing the request.

* Numbers: Cast parameters to integers if you expect IDs.

$id = (int)$_GET['id'];

* Text: Use regular expressions (preg_match) to ensure fields like usernames only contain alphanumeric characters.

## 4. Secure Session Cookies
Prevent attackers from stealing session identifiers via JavaScript by locking down your session configuration.

* Configure your php.ini file or set them at the top of your master PHP file:

ini_set('session.cookie_httponly', 1); // Prevents JavaScript from reading the cookie
ini_set('session.cookie_secure', 1);   // Ensures cookies only travel over HTTPS
ini_set('session.cookie_samesite', 'Strict'); // Protects against CSRF


